			<!-- more about her -->
			<div class="she">
<h2>Linda G. Greenberg</h3>
<p>
Linda’s hometown is Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts. As a teenager, she was a lifeguard and would catch lobsters with her father along the Cape Cod Canal. She comes from a big Jewish family, and is the sixth out of seven children. She graduated from the University of Massachusetts with two undergraduate degrees (Political Science and Education/Human Services). After college, Linda did a VISTA-type experience, working with Navajo elders in Flagstaff, Arizona for a couple of years. While in Flagstaff, she led hiking trips in the Grand Canyon and river trips down the Colorado River. She moved to DC and worked as an editor and writer for a health policy journal, which inspired her to go to graduate school. In 1991, she left DC to pursue a doctoral degree in social welfare policy at Brandeis University in Waltham, Massachusetts. Linda loved living in Boston and being able to travel home to the Cape. After she completed her dissertation in 1996, she migrated south to New York City to work at a private foundation. In 1998, Linda moved further south, by accepting a job in Baltimore at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS), the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (the same agency that gave her a grant to write her dissertation). In 2003, Linda took a sabbatical to work with Senator Kennedy’s health policy office, which motivated her to move closer to DC (to Bethesda from Baltimore).  Linda met Tac in 2005 at a Bike & Brunch barbeque and they became cycling friends. She worked, she played, and one day in 2009, she realized her interest in Tac was more than just as cycling friends. For almost 3 years, Linda and Tac have been true companions, enjoying foreign travel and every day life.  Linda moved farther south (all the way to Dupont Circle) in November 2011, and is calm and happy about how she and Tac are composing a life together.
</p>
